PART (I)

Alas, now I know
that my heart yearns for you
and your shiny, round marbles
of crystalline blue,

and I see, ‘tween the lines
of a soft, satin song,
that you’re just so right,
but the time’s just so wrong.

My words seemed too strong,
and they carried such weight;
I see now they’re too little,
and far, far too late,

and I rue, though in vain,
o’er our newfound estrangement,
so regretfully spurred
by my east coast arrangement.

And I know I won’t see you
for many long days,
but on cloud-shadowed oceans
like your stormy eyes’ gaze,

with the tide pulling gently,
away from the shore,
toward deep-water canyons
where busy boats moor.

And I hope that, someday,
if our paths again cross,
that you’ll share your new grooves
that new ages emboss,

and please know, as you catch
the ambitions you chase,
your sweet, cherished memory
won’t soon be erased.

PART (II)

I strayed five hundred miles
from my sunny-sky home,
but the sound of your laugh
and your voice on the phone
made me smile so wide.
and feel so unalone.

I returned, as did you –
I to my castle,
and you to my arms –
only to find you, a ghost,
guiding me out of danger,
but melting away, abruptly
into the bible-black dawn.

I see, cast o’er the overcast sea, eyes –
stormy, embattled, suspended in turmoil –
bearing witness to triumphant waves
as they salt the with'ring iceplant
that sprawls above the tideline,
which rises coarsely with ev’ry passing season.

I’m bound for Delaware, true,
but dear Ella, where are you?
